      <hedline>
        <hl1>Women at the Wheel As Ambulance Drivers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ellen Rubin letter on recent article about women sport utility drivers recalls her days as volunteer ambulance driver (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I raised my children in Scarsdale before the advent of the S.U.V., yet I had the opportunity to be ''the toughest guy on the road.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I raised my children in Scarsdale before the advent of the S.U.V., yet I had the opportunity to be ''the toughest guy on the road.''</p>
        <p>For 20 years, I have driven an ambulance for the Scarsdale Volunteer Ambulance Corps. There are many women like myself who have been called ''The Ladies of the Day,'' covering the 24-hour schedule as drivers and EMT's while our children are at school. If ''size is no longer a fear,'' and you don't want to look like ''a mom,'' join us at 723-3003. We are in great need of ambulance drivers. Be the one to flash the lights and make everyone get out of your way, and at the same time, do a service for the community.</p>
        <p>ELLEN RUBIN  Scarsdale</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
